 reflection target might complicate matters regarding metadata in a native runtime. Also, will filtering affect the inclusion of test classes?\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring constructor registrations**\\\\n\\\\nDo constructors need to be registered? In a native image, reflection may not work on application or test classes unless all public methods are available. Actually, Class.getConstructor requires metadata. JUnit seems to register constructors, but I’m not sure about nested classes. My initial idea was to use the test class since JUnit registers its constructor metadata, but there's the issue with having two constructors. What if I keep one for XMLStreamWriter? JUnit generally needs a single zero-arg constructor, but that conflicts with createStAXResult. Could I introduce a second non-public class for XMLStreamWriter?\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Determining constructor access**\\\\n\\\\nThe dynamic-access report is indicating it wants execution, but I see that the agent filter only impacts the generated configuration and not static analysis. I think I’ll use a top-level package-private class, CustomStAXResult, which doesn't have a $ in its name. But can I have a public constructor for getConstructor if the class is package-private? I recall that getConstructor should return public constructors for public classes, but maybe it will still work for package-private classes? I'll have to test this conceptually to avoid a NoSuchMethod error.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating test class design**\\\\n\\\\nI’m considering creating a top-level test as a StAX subclass that relies on JUnit to register the test class. One approach could be making a public test class with just a zero-argument constructor while also including a static public method. However, I'm running into a snag since I can't have an XMLStreamWriter constructor. So, I'm exploring how to design this effectively while keeping all necessary functionality intact.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Testing Java class behavior**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about whether I can annotate @TestInstance without a JUnit resolver. It seems like it wouldn't be necessary. Perhaps I could create a second public class in the same file, but Java doesn't allow that. Maybe I should look into using getConstructor on a package-private class that has a public constructor. It sounds like I should test this with jshell and use bash for a quick check. Let's see what happens!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_YwiutEylXhihiJ6KxkjJizE8|fc_05ea79250a80ec6e0169f61e9b385481909ad7e12b4b014708\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"tmp=$(mktemp -d); cat > $tmp/Test.java <<'EOF'\\nclass Hidden {\\n  public Hidden(String s) {}\\n}\\npublic class Test {\\n public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception { System.out.println(Hidden.class.getConstructor(String.class)); }\\n}\\nEOF\\njavac $tmp/Test.java && java -cp $tmp Test\", \"timeout\": 10}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 1645, \"output\": 1191, \"cacheRead\": 51712, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 54548, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777737353047, \"responseId\": \"resp_05ea79250a80ec6e0169f61e89a004819080c377310eb03ce3\"}}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.hsqldb:hsqldb:2.4.1/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-02T15-52-31-091353Z.log:4501:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering test class structure**\\n\\nI need a single constructor for JUnit, but having my top-level test class extend StAXResult with two constructors causes some issues. It seems I need a custom StAXResult subclass instead. I’m questioning whether I can have inner helper classes when the guidelines say not to use $ in test class names. But maybe it’s fine if it compiles? The dynamic access to my reflection target might complicate matters regarding metadata in a native runtime. Also, will filtering affect the inclusion of test classes?\\n\\n**Exploring constructor registrations**\\n\\nDo constructors need to be registered? In a native image, reflection may not work on application or test classes unless all public methods are available. Actually, Class.getConstructor requires metadata. JUnit seems to register constructors, but I’m not sure about nested classes. My initial idea was to use the test class since JUnit registers its constructor metadata, but there's the issue with having two constructors. What if I keep one for XMLStreamWriter? JUnit generally needs a single zero-arg constructor, but that conflicts with createStAXResult. Could I introduce a second non-public class for XMLStreamWriter?\\n\\n**Determining constructor access**\\n\\nThe dynamic-access report is indicating it wants execution, but I see that the agent filter only impacts the generated configuration and not static analysis. I think I’ll use a top-level package-private class, CustomStAXResult, which doesn't have a $ in its name. But can I have a public constructor for getConstructor if the class is package-private? I recall that getConstructor should return public constructors for public classes, but maybe it will still work for package-private classes? I'll have to test this conceptually to avoid a NoSuchMethod error.\\n\\n**Evaluating test class design**\\n\\nI’m considering creating a top-level test as a StAX subclass that relies on JUnit to register the test class. One approach could be making a public test class with just a zero-argument constructor while also including a static public method. However, I'm running into a snag since I can't have an XMLStreamWriter constructor. So, I'm exploring how to design this effectively while keeping all necessary functionality intact.\\n\\n**Testing Java class behavior**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether I can annotate @TestInstance without a JUnit resolver. It seems like it wouldn't be necessary. Perhaps I could create a second public class in the same file, but Java doesn't allow that. Maybe I should look into using getConstructor on a package-private class that has a public constructor. It sounds like I should test this with jshell and use bash for a quick check. Let's see what happens!\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_05ea79250a80ec6e0169f61e8a5d348190bc3fe66da93e8a4f\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp9h6bJLPc_Y2ew6is0vjP0blH5NDvQRZmGrYN0Z-Gn9GFD3Vz1lFP61FiZLa3uQAQOeHyXxkl5b4apk8wN81p8o9ClauCdGEaSpZBfYBIsTSUW1T3cgHZc10TcmBTTEyOl9pF6ryHjvyqnQKp8hnwyTdDYwP902t6dA-OPLQ0v5Ov7rFGxxVxm8SwFWgG4U5J_pyKhIgMLVeRe5T4FaYFVNcRgxGcKBJ-qDGx4haW83UA1fUz_7P_h4CjKxD02G__aVI50eXbLpnwHaXJyfY0YHHJpPRvniNQq8x9M1l6kj1QKpYDZt1Uva03nJCqGbtGixB4oobRv1CTG3zo0K1Jm2Ep4bjKeZ7xE-1IWPqFZjdkZA3EDQwHpE9AZW8H3wVHP5KBEtnfDLlhRyCrXInRCzbbaMI8RXwazZ7l5_5PQFwQ07_P5lqHS3r8Snu7uQjfBfCRfNmCta3hFvluU6P1_Vs1bNqn8FbTMp3JCZAruVMRMUprCYeMbgLkat_n_whT2-X0zaVNICOtj0Muk6qKuMxKn7mNYo-XALWczyRRJyCZrzwmaClJ5sYz8nFCimhLl3f9WKjGdUYpZFKzjZPGb_6TyrEEJMDoZBxe6roOIivvo_2D4KF2f-U3FEg18hgrrVhVRbr9kB5daPKJXYRf3Tyb_zCBrpaKPWS2Es7w66TRB1vQVkHqhTTpYqY9U48nIre6yW8TGB4xuNXdg1tTUGjALzLFOxW_PlQJJWiqaYCNMLr41pWNWQFASbbocMGRDnYikWEtpcAGdMZmjWk0z_3-FTFkBbmcZcQprv0foO-TZuavOjKNyTQFYkVpHA6mMsuiv-mJi0t__LQA19iLMb1rEyDE9P-m8ou16GU1QHghb8S33r0r12W8_K7VxlXXxgyGj6kmBVbO1iJcZ5Cl4IKpH4grF796OLnR2g-6zmM3JA1yYVeQomLridJpWJRj0VVHY5l7CaiTLAzdQ6rgztp8oCuhOe-PtpYbixfcrxW_b_S-UgkEuWZKv5KdgciEQwSv50B5t7zVO8MfDHVGVO7QBdSArtlrPfCLFOZ4ptx7rF45p6AIU2cUYiMdFKPtwzJ0XbsU06Xb0TG19I9Aw_XPZAcmeFOuJTfByUlKl_yN-B4F2mD09ylK5XAqTPSOGL6j6gxDVuY3zY7kXPKcJEYdIYIqLvoS7ygtzYxZe-ZOh2dwx7qyoPR6r7599185bPLm00_zv9GnJXSwHbUWr5xWFpkomHEbuyl5edg_GXS7DFMTODnKD6zZ2nGvUl3uEPoJ2IzWp6ZU_l56H-CZefvKbNva6WPoxlJiLrHs